article.headline: Mystics beat Sting for second time in three nights
article.linkText: Mystics overcome first-half hole, rout Sting
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Coach Richie Adubato never stopped believing
in his Washington Mystics, and his faith was rewarded.

Rookie Temeka Johnson and Alana Beard had 14 points apiece, and
the Mystics overcame a 12-point first-half deficit to beat the
Charlotte Sting 65-50 Thursday night.

"We knew we would shoot the ball better," Adubato said.

Beard added seven rebounds as the Mystics (8-7) topped the Sting
(2-11) for the second time in three nights.

Down 27-20, Washington opened the second half with a 14-6 spurt,
including a jumper by Johnson that made it 34-33 with 13:57
remaining -- the Mystics' first lead since the opening half.

With 9:14 to play, Sting center Tammy Sutton-Brown picked up her
fifth personal foul and left the game for good. Without her
guarding the paint for Charlotte, Washington pulled away down the
stretch.

"The first half we were ice cold. We executed our offense but
just couldn't hit our shots. That'll happen some games," Beard
said. "Fortunately, we played good defense down the stretch, and
we were able to come away with some steals and loose balls."

Tangela Smith had 21 points to lead the Sting, while
Sutton-Brown added 15 points in 23 minutes of play.

"It was a tale of two halves," Sting coach Trudi Lacey said.
"They stepped up the pressure, became very physical and we turned
the ball over late."

The Sting took control midway through the first half, thanks to
an 11-2 run capped by Smith's layup that gave Charlotte a 21-13
lead. The Sting led by 27-15 until Beard's jumper and three free
throws by Chasity Melvin made it 27-20 at halftime.

Washington shot just 39.6 percent in the first half, while
Charlotte made 40.7 percent of its shots.
